  "prompt": "What's your review on harry potter and the cursed child?",
  "response": "As an AI, I don't have personal opinions, but I can provide a summary of general sentiments and critiques surrounding \"Harry Potter and the Cursed Child.\"\n\n\"Harry Potter and the Cursed Child\" is a stage play written by Jack Thorne, based on an original story by J.K. Rowling, John Tiffany, and Jack Thorne. The play premiered in London in 2016 and has been performed in various locations worldwide. It is also available in a published script format.\n\nHere are some common points from reviews and critiques:\n\n**Plot and Storyline:**\n- The story picks up where the seventh book, \"Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows,\" left off, focusing on Harry Potter's son, Albus Severus Potter, and his struggles with living up to his father's legacy.\n- Some fans appreciate the continuation of the beloved characters and the exploration of new themes, such as father-son relationships and the complexities of living in the shadow of a famous parent.\n- However, some fans and critics argue that the plot relies heavily on time travel and contains elements that feel inconsistent with the original series, leading to mixed reactions.\n\n**Character Development:**\n- The play introduces new characters and provides a deeper look into the lives of the original characters as adults.\n- While some enjoy the development of characters like Scorpius Malfoy, others feel that certain characterizations, particularly of Harry, Hermione, and Ron, do not align with their established personalities from the books.\n\n**Production and Presentation:**\n- The stage production has been widely praised for its impressive special effects, staging, and choreography, which bring the magical world to life in a unique and captivating way.\n- The visual spectacle and innovative use of stagecraft have been highlighted as major strengths of the play.\n\n**Reception:**\n- \"Harry Potter and the Cursed Child\" has received numerous awards and nominations, including the Laurence Olivier Awards and Tony Awards.\n- The play has been a commercial success, attracting fans of the original series and theater enthusiasts alike.\n\nOverall, while \"Harry Potter and the Cursed Child\" has garnered praise for its production quality and the opportunity to revisit the Wizarding World, it has also faced criticism for its storyline and character portrayals. Fans of the original series may have varying opinions on whether the play lives up to their expectations.",
